China is compelling Tibetan herders to abandon their nomadic lifestyle for urban settlement to facilitate development, resulting in loss of livelihood.
The government cites overgrazing as the reason, causing erosion and desertification.
Tibetan communities are being uprooted for mining and infrastructure projects.
The relocation program aims to combat desert expansion, a pressing issue in China.
Soil erosion affects vast areas, threatening agriculture.
Efforts to reverse erosion include afforestation and soil conservation projects.
The government vows to protect arable land and improve farmers' lives.
Despite challenges, progress has been made in reversing soil erosion, benefiting millions of residents.
